Advancing Musculoskeletal Health in Cancer Survivorship

I’m Devon Cataldi, an epidemiologist and body‑composition scientist. I build measurement‑precise models—integrating imaging (DXA, 3D optical, BIA), biomarkers (D3-creatine; metabolomics), and physical‑activity data—to predict outcomes in aging and cancer survivorship.

✉ Email LinkedIn Google Scholar

About & Photos

Postdoctoral Research Fellow focused on body composition, musculoskeletal health, and cancer survivorship. Licensed athletic trainer (HI, PA); educator and mentor committed to health equity and community engagement.

Research Focus

Three pillars guide my work: measurement precision in body composition, musculoskeletal health across aging and cancer, and predictive modeling for targeted interventions.

Pillar 1

Precision Body‑Composition Assessment

Head‑to‑head comparisons and multicompartment models using DXA, D2O, BIA, 3D optical, and D3‑creatine to reduce bias and improve clinical utility.

Pillar 2

Musculoskeletal Health in Survivorship

Large‑scale cohort analyses (MEC/APS) linking lean & bone mass, fat distribution, and physical activity with survival and functional outcomes in breast‑cancer survivors.

Pillar 3

Predictive Analytics & Omics

Integrating metabolomics with imaging and activity data; applying ML to identify high‑risk phenotypes and inform precision exercise/nutrition interventions.

Clinical Nutrition • 2024 • First author
Accuracy and precision of multiple body composition methods and associations with muscle strength (The Da Kine Study).
Journal of Nutrition • 2022 • First author
Agreement and precision of deuterium dilution for total body water & multicompartment body composition in athletes.
Communications Medicine • 2024 • Co‑author
Deep learning of 3D surface scans to understand local fat/muscle distributions and health.
